━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
                    WRITTEN SUBMISSION ON BEHALF OF THE PETITIONER
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

May it please Your Lordships,

The Petitioner, through his learned counsel, most respectfully submits this
Written Submission in support of the present petition seeking quashing of the
criminal proceedings arising from FIR No. 496/2011 dated 28-12-2011, currently
pending as Special Session Case No. 1/2025 before the learned Special Session
Judge (Prevention of Corruption Act), Udaipur.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
I.  BRIEF FACTS
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

The Petitioner is the Director of M/s Praman Construction Pvt. Ltd., which was
awarded a contract in 2011 for repair and construction work at Maharana Pratap
Stadium, Udaipur. On 28-12-2011, during a period of heavy rainfall and storm,
a portion of the stadium's outer wall partially collapsed. The prosecution's
entire case rests on a single Forensic Science Laboratory (FSL) report which
declared certain cement mortar samples as "failed." The Petitioner submits that
this FSL report is fundamentally unreliable and cannot form the basis of any
criminal prosecution, for the reasons set out hereinbelow.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
II.  SUBMISSION I — CHAIN-OF-CUSTODY DEFECTS RENDER THE FSL REPORT INADMISSIBLE
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

The most fundamental infirmity in the prosecution's case is the complete absence
of any chain-of-custody documentation for the cement mortar samples that form
the basis of the FSL report. The prosecution has not produced — and, it is
submitted, cannot produce — any record showing who collected the samples, from
which precise locations, at what time, in what manner, how they were sealed,
how they were transported to the laboratory, who received them at the FSL, under
what storage conditions they were kept, and who handled them at each stage of
the testing process. This is not a minor procedural lapse; it is a foundational
evidentiary failure that strikes at the very root of the prosecution's case.

The Hon'ble Supreme Court of India, in its landmark judgment in Kattavellai @
Devakar v. State of Tamil Nadu, Criminal Appeal No. 1672 of 2019, decided on
15 July 2025 (2025 INSC 845), delivered by a three-judge bench comprising
Hon'ble Justice Vikram Nath, Hon'ble Justice Sanjay Karol, and Hon'ble Justice
Sandeep Mehta, laid down binding nationwide guidelines for the maintenance of
chain-of-custody in forensic evidence. The Court held in unambiguous terms:
"Right from the point of collection to the logical end, i.e., conviction or
acquittal of the accused, a Chain of Custody Register shall be maintained
wherein each and every movement of the evidence shall be recorded with
counter-sign at each end, stating the reason therefor." The Court further
directed all State DGPs to prepare Chain of Custody Register forms and
circulate them to all districts with clear instructions to ensure the integrity
and reliability of forensic samples. This judgment is binding precedent across
India and applies with full force to the present case.

In the present case, not a single link in the chain of custody has been
documented. There is no sealing memo, no sample identification record, no
dispatch register, no malkhana entry, no FSL inward register, no seal
verification letter, and no analyst worksheet. The prosecution has not even
disclosed the name of the officer who collected the samples. In the absence of
this unbroken documentary chain, it is impossible to establish that the samples
tested by the FSL were the same samples collected from the stadium site, that
they were not contaminated or tampered with in transit, or that the test results
reflect the actual condition of the mortar at the time of construction. The FSL
report, built on this evidentiary vacuum, cannot be treated as reliable or
conclusive evidence against the Petitioner.

The principle that chain-of-custody defects vitiate forensic evidence has also
been affirmed by the Hon'ble Uttarakhand High Court in its judgment reported in
LiveLaw dated 28 March 2026, where the Court held: "A conviction must rest on
legally proved evidence and not suspicion, however strong, and that in the
absence of a duly established chain of custody, forensic evidence loses its
evidentiary value and cannot be treated as conclusive." While this judgment
arises from a different factual context, the principle it enunciates is of
universal application and is directly relevant to the present case.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
III.  SUBMISSION II — UNILATERAL EX-PARTE SAMPLING VIOLATES MANDATORY PROTOCOLS
      AND THE PRINCIPLE OF NATURAL JUSTICE
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

The samples in the present case were collected entirely ex-parte, without any
notice to or presence of the Petitioner or his authorised representative. This
is not merely a procedural irregularity; it is a violation of mandatory
requirements prescribed by the Bureau of Indian Standards and the Central Public
Works Department, which are binding on all public works investigations in India.

Clause 4.1 of IS 3535:1986 — "Methods of Sampling Hydraulic Cements" —
expressly mandates that "the supplier's representative shall be present at the
time of sampling unless otherwise agreed upon in writing." No such written
agreement exists on record. Sections 3.7.4 and 12.2.1 of the CPWD Works Manual
2023 similarly mandate joint sampling by the Engineer-in-Charge and the
Contractor, with samples sealed bearing the signatures of both parties. Neither
requirement was complied with. The Petitioner was never notified of the sampling
exercise, was never given an opportunity to be present, and was never given an
opportunity to challenge the sampling methodology or to demand parallel testing.

The significance of this violation cannot be overstated. The right to be present
at the collection of evidence that may be used against one is a facet of the
fundamental principle of natural justice — audi alteram partem. Where a
contractor's representative is excluded from the sampling process, the
contractor is deprived of the ability to verify that the samples were taken from
representative locations, that the correct methodology was followed, that the
samples were not contaminated, and that the sealing was done properly. The
entire forensic exercise becomes a one-sided affair, the results of which the
accused has no means of independently verifying or challenging.

The Hon'ble Supreme Court in State of Punjab v. Baldev Singh, (1999) 6 SCC 172,
while dealing with mandatory procedural safeguards under the NDPS Act, held that
where a statute or official manual prescribes a specific procedure for the
collection of evidence, strict compliance is not merely directory but mandatory,
and departure therefrom creates a presumption of prejudice to the accused. The
principle is directly applicable here: the mandatory requirements of IS 3535:1986
and the CPWD Manual were not followed, and the Petitioner has been irreparably
prejudiced by his exclusion from the sampling process.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
IV.  SUBMISSION III — NON-COMPLIANCE WITH BIS/CPWD PROTOCOLS AND APPLICATION
     OF THE WRONG STANDARD VITIATE THE SCIENTIFIC FOUNDATION OF THE FSL REPORT
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

The FSL report suffers from a foundational scientific error that renders it
worthless as evidence: the prosecution applied IS 1199:2018 — "Methods of
Sampling and Analysis of Fresh Concrete" — to hardened masonry mortar in
existing stone masonry. IS 1199:2018 explicitly applies only to fresh concrete.
It has no application whatsoever to hardened cement mortar that has been in
place for years in an existing masonry structure. The correct Indian standard
for masonry mortar is IS 2250:1981 — "Code of Practice for Preparation and Use
of Masonry Mortars." The correct international standard for forensic examination
of hardened masonry mortar is ASTM C1324 — "Standard Test Method for
Examination and Analysis of Hardened Masonry Mortar." Neither was applied.

The consequences of this error are severe. ASTM C1324, Sections 7 and 8,
mandates that before sampling hardened mortar joints, the carbonated outer layer
— which in mortar joints over fifteen years old can extend to a depth of 10 to
15 millimetres — must be removed, because this carbonated layer has a
compressive strength 30 to 50 per cent lower than the original mortar. If
samples are taken from the outer surface without removing this layer, they will
invariably "fail" strength tests — not because the original construction was
defective, but because of natural weathering over time. The prosecution's
samples appear to have been taken from the outer surface of the mortar joints
without any removal of the carbonated layer, which means the "failure" recorded
in the FSL report reflects nothing more than the natural ageing of the structure.

Compounding this error, the samples were collected on 28-12-2011 during heavy
rainfall and storm conditions. IS 4031 (Part 6) mandates a temperature of
27±2°C and controlled humidity for compressive strength testing. ASTM C780,
Section 6.1, states in terms: "Samples must be protected from rain and moisture;
otherwise sample is invalid." BS EN 1015-2, Section 4.3.1, classifies weather
protection as a "Mandatory Precondition" for valid sampling. None of these
requirements could have been met during a storm. The samples were therefore
contaminated by rain moisture from the moment of collection, making any
subsequent laboratory test result unreliable.

The Hon'ble Supreme Court in State of Maharashtra v. Damu, (2000) 6 SCC 269,
held that where the foundational facts upon which an expert opinion is based are
themselves unreliable or contaminated, the expert opinion built thereon cannot
be treated as conclusive evidence. The Court emphasised that the reliability of
forensic evidence depends entirely on the integrity of the collection and
preservation process. In the present case, the collection process was vitiated
by the application of the wrong standard, the failure to remove the carbonated
outer layer, and the exposure of samples to rain and storm conditions. The FSL
report, built on these contaminated foundations, cannot be treated as reliable
expert opinion under Section 45 of the Bhartiya Sakshya Adhiniyam, 2023.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
V.   SUBMISSION IV — ABSENCE OF CONTEMPORANEOUS RECORDS AND SITE-INSPECTION
     LOGS CREATES AN INCURABLE DEFECT; THIS COURT'S OWN PRECEDENTS ON
     STRUCTURAL SAFETY ESTABLISH WEATHER AS AN INDEPENDENT CAUSATIVE FACTOR
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

The prosecution has not produced any contemporaneous records of the sampling
process or of the site inspection that preceded it. There is no spot memo, no
site inspection log, no panchnama prepared at the sampling site, no photographs
of the extraction process, no record of the weather conditions at the time of
sampling, no IMD weather data for 28-12-2011, and no record of the structural
condition of the wall before the collapse. The absence of a panchnama is
particularly fatal. The Hon'ble Supreme Court in State of Maharashtra v. Damu,
(2000) 6 SCC 269, held that where the prosecution relies heavily on a forensic
report, the foundational burden lies on the prosecution to prove beyond
reasonable doubt that the samples sent to the laboratory were exactly the same
as those collected from the spot. Without a panchnama prepared at the site in
the presence of independent witnesses, this burden cannot be discharged. The
prosecution cannot establish the identity of the samples, and the FSL report
therefore rests on an unverifiable foundation.

The absence of a site-inspection log is equally significant. Without a
contemporaneous record of the structural condition of the wall before and after
the collapse, it is impossible to determine whether the collapse was caused by
any defect in the Petitioner's construction work or by the extreme weather
conditions that prevailed on 28-12-2011. The National Building Code 2016/2023,
Section 3.4, and the CPWD Manual Appendix C classify extreme weather events as
Force Majeure, exempting contractors from liability for damage caused thereby.
The prosecution has made no attempt to exclude weather as the proximate cause
of the collapse, and without a site-inspection log, it cannot do so.

In this context, it is respectfully submitted that this Hon'ble Court's own
judicial notice in its suo motu PIL proceedings is directly relevant. On 29 July
2025, this Hon'ble Court took suo motu cognizance of the tragic collapse of a
government school building in Piplodi village, Banswara district, Rajasthan, in
which seven schoolchildren lost their lives on 25 July 2025. In the subsequent
order dated 23 August 2025, this Hon'ble Court directed the closure of 86,934
dilapidated classrooms across Rajasthan and demanded a roadmap for the repair
of unsafe school buildings, observing: "Building safe schools should be priority
for architects, engineers, policy makers, administrators and emergency response
planners." In the continuing proceedings through 2025 and 2026, this Hon'ble
Court has repeatedly taken judicial notice of the fact that structural collapses
in Rajasthan are caused by a combination of extreme weather events, pre-existing
structural deterioration, and maintenance failures — and has criticised the
State for failing to address these systemic causes.

The significance of this Court's own findings cannot be overstated. If this
Hon'ble Court has judicially noticed that thousands of public structures in
Rajasthan are unsafe due to age, maintenance failure, and extreme weather — and
has directed the State to prepare a roadmap for their repair — it cannot
simultaneously permit a criminal prosecution of a contractor for a collapse that
occurred during a storm, on the basis of a forensic report that is vitiated by
the defects described above. The Petitioner submits that the collapse of the
stadium wall on 28-12-2011 was caused by the same combination of extreme weather
and pre-existing structural factors that this Court has recognised as systemic
in Rajasthan, and that the prosecution's attempt to attribute criminal liability
to the Petitioner on the basis of a defective FSL report is an abuse of the
process of law.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
VI.  SUBMISSION V — NO PRIMA FACIE CASE; DISCHARGE IS MANDATORY
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

The cumulative effect of the defects described above is that the prosecution's
case rests entirely on a single FSL report that is inadmissible, unreliable, and
scientifically unsound. There is no independent evidence of corruption, bribery,
or criminal intent. There is no evidence that the Petitioner was responsible for
the collapse as opposed to the extreme weather conditions. There is no evidence
that the construction work was defective in any respect that was not attributable
to the natural ageing of the structure or to Force Majeure.

The Hon'ble Supreme Court in Union of India v. Prafulla Kumar Samal, (1979) 3
SCC 4, Para 10, held: "If the material placed on record discloses nothing more
than a suspicion, the accused is entitled to be discharged." The Hon'ble Supreme
Court in State of Bihar v. Ramesh Singh, (1977) 4 SCC 39, Para 5, held that at
the stage of discharge, the Court must satisfy itself that the material produced
makes out a prima facie case; if the material discloses nothing more than
suspicion, discharge is mandatory. In the present case, the prosecution's
material — even taken at its highest — discloses nothing more than suspicion.
The Petitioner is therefore entitled to be discharged under Section 250 of the
Bhartiya Nagarik Suraksha Sanhita, 2023 (erstwhile Section 227 Cr.P.C.).

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
VII.  PRAYER
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

In view of the foregoing, it is most respectfully prayed that this Hon'ble Court
may be pleased to: (i) quash and set aside the criminal proceedings in Special
Session Case No. 1/2025 pending before the learned Special Session Judge (PCA),
Udaipur, as the same are an abuse of the process of law and no prima facie case
is made out against the Petitioner; (ii) alternatively, direct the learned trial
court to discharge the Petitioner under Section 250 BNSS 2023; (iii) direct the
prosecution to produce all original records of sample collection, sealing,
transport, FSL receipt, and testing, failing which adverse inference be drawn
under Section 114 of the Bhartiya Sakshya Adhiniyam, 2023; and (iv) pass such
other and further orders as this Hon'ble Court may deem fit and proper in the
facts and circumstances of the case.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
